  <li id="comment-22726" class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn">Anonymous</cite></div>
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2010/07/summer-list/#comment-22726"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2010-07-07T17:23:07-04:00">Wednesday, July 7, 2010 at 5:23 pm</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>Iced coffee was the thing that made me go past my coyness and leave a comment after reading you for I don&#39;t know how many years!!!</p>
<p>But when you feel like one&#8230; try this &#8230; and you will never regret it!</p>
<p>All you will need is a glass of half an half milk, a double espresso, sugar if you take any in your coffee, cinnamon if you like it in your cappucino 🙂</p>
<p>and something that will resemble this: <a href="http://www.hamiltonbeach.com/kitchen-appliances-drink-mixers.html" rel="nofollow ugc">http://www.hamiltonbeach.com/kitchen-appliances-drink-mixers.html</a></p>
<p>you will pour the cold milk &#8211; it has to be cold &#8211; in the drink mixer for about 10 mins till it thickens and gets like cream </p>
<p>you will pour your double super strong espresso (after you have added as much sugar as you want while it is hot) over ice.</p>
<p>then you will add as much as you want from the creamed milk. I usually make it in a long, flute glass and fill it with the creamed milk to the top.</p>
<p>sprinkle some cinnamon on top if you like.</p>
<p>really&#8230;it may sound weird, but I know you will enjoy it.</p>
<p>with lots of admiration and sunshine 🙂</p>
<p>argyro from athens, greece</p>
    </div>

